Capillary copper tubes of 3/16 inch (OD: 4.8 mm and thickness: 0.8 mm, as per ASTM B280 standards) were inserted through the PCM between the Li-Ion cells as shown in Fig. 3c. The number of copper tubes was varied to influence the thermal conductivity of the cooling mass. The thermal conductivity for paraffin is 0.2 W/m K and for copper 386 W/m K. Effective thermal conductivity of PCC cooling mass was calculated using Eqs. (1) and (2) and by referring to previous works [26]. Copper tubes were placed at equidistance and the number of tubes was chosen as 3, 5 and 7, so as to provide a sufficient gap to fill the paraffin. Effective thermal conductivity for 3, 5 and 7 tubes was 15.4, 24.1 and 34.2 W/m K, respectively. By inserting seven copper tubes, the thermal conductivity of PCM increased 171 times of its pure value. In case of Li et al., it can be noticed that the effective thermal conductivity of PCM–metal composite was 218 times of the pure value of PCM [29].1Keff=(1-ε)Kpcm+εKmetal,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
